Trading activities on the Nigerian equities market yesterday closed on a bearish note, to extend the negative sentiments to three consecutive trading days, on losses in Airtel Africa and 24 others. In summary, the All-Share Index (ASI) decreased by 577.43 absolute points, representing a decline of 1.48 per cent to close at 38,445.09 points. While the overall market capitalisation value lost N301 billion to close at N20.038 trillion. The market downturn was driven by price depreciation in large and medium capitalised stocks amongst which are; Airtel Africa, BOC Gases, Dangote Cement, Dangote Sugar Refinery and Northern Nigeria Flour Mills (NNFM). Analysts at Afrinvest Limited noted that “In the coming trading session, we expect the local bourse to extend the bearish performance.” As measured by market breadth, market sentiment closed negative, as 25 stocks declined, relative to 23 gainers. MRS Oil Nigeria and Seplat Petroleum Development Company (SEPLAT) recorded the highest price gain of 10 per cent each to close at N12.10 and N682.00, while Sterling Bank followed with a gain 9.74 per cent to close at N1.69, per share. Japaul Gold and Ventures rose by 9.62 per cent to close at 57 kobo, while Regency Alliance Insurance appreciated by 8.82 per cent to close at 37 kobo, per share. On the other hand, C&I Leasing and Airtel Africa led the losers’ chart by 10 per cent each to close at N4.50 and N837.00, while BOC Gases followed with a decline of 9.96 per cent to close at N11.03, per share. Royal Exchange shed 9.64 per cent to close at 75 kobo, while NNFM depreciated by 8.94 per cent to close at N5.60, per share.